A big thank you to Mera, founder of Soapply for coming on LIVE and sharing the soapply story and more about The Defined Dish x Soapply impact!

Each set sold is tied to a $10 donation that funds the launch of Soapply's new water, sanitation, and hygiene projects at their newest impact zone in West Bengal, India!⁠⁠
⁠⁠
With our goal of $15,000, we will fund 3 handwashing stations, 3 drinking stations, 1 ultra-filtration water system, the construction of a toilet block, hygiene training for teachers, and a student hygiene club—tap to shop for change + help us reach our goal!

node.text:
My take on the Classic AUSTIN cocktail! 
INGREDIENTS
3 ounces Reposado Tequila (or 2 "big jiggers" full)— I use @flechaazultequila 
1.5 ounces Cointreau (or 1 "big jigger" full)
1.5 ounces fresh-squeezed lime juice (or 1 "big jigger" full)
.5 ounce martini olive brine juice (from the jar) (about 1/2 "small jigger" full)
.3 ounces fresh-squeezed orange juice (a little less than 1/2 "small jigger" full)
salt, for serving on the rim
fresh lime wedges, for serving
martini olives, for serving

INSTRUCTIONS
Fill a cocktail shaker full of ice. Add the tequila, cointreau, lime juice, olive brine, and orange juice. Close, seal and shake until very cold.
Salt the rim of just half of 2 martini glasses. Pour the martini into the glass. Serve with a wedge of lime and a few olives on a toothpick or cocktail pick.

https://thedefineddish.com/mexican-martini/

How to make SCRAPPY BONE BROTH IG tv edition. 🎥

Here is a quick demo showing how I save scraps throughout the week in a ziplock bag in my freezer so that I can make bone broth. Not only is it cheaper than buying store bought broth, but the flavor and it’s nutritional benefits are much stronger too! 
Read this blog post if you’re curious the benefits of bone broth/ what it is exactly. http://www.thedefineddish.com/bone-broth-why-and-how-i-drink-it/

Here are some very classic/traditional things I throw into my scrap bag to make bone broth: -leftover roasted chicken bones/carcass. Must be roasted, if it’s not previously roasted the flavor is ick. •celery stalks •carrots •onion scraps, shallot, etc •garlic •ginger •parsley stems •thyme, rosemary (dried or fresh works)

Throw all of those items that you have, there is not specific guidelines to what goes in. Now fill the pot until the contents are just covered with water by about 1.5 inches. Throw in a splash of apple cider vinegar, a few bay leaves, and about a tbsp black peppercorns. Bring to a boil, reduce heat to simmer and cook, covered, for 12-24 hours. 
Storing tips: strain the broth and let cool completely before storing. NOTE if you store in glass mason jars be sure it’s 100% cooled and only filled 3/4 of the way before freezing! The broth will expand and break the glass and all your hard work will be trashed 😓
You can freeze for up to 3 months. And I usually keep mine in the fridge for 7-10 days. 
FAQ:
YES you can do this in an instant pot. I’d go 180 minutes and let pressure release on its own. 
YES you can do in a crockpot, on low for 12-24 hours 
Ok, let me know your bone broth questions below!

Had the best time with my @sietefoods fam, giving them a sneak peek of a great weeknight dish from my upcoming cookbook, Chipotle Chicken Tostadas with Pineapple Salsa! 
Simple, bursting with flavor and better for you— exactly what the intention behind my book was. Checkout the full IGTV video and I’ll go ahead and give you a sneak peek of the full recipe below! And a big thank you to @sietefoods for making the best of the best and always supporting me. You have my ❤️ #

Chipotle Chicken Tostadas w/ Pineapple Slaw ⬇️ 2 c small diced fresh pineapple
¼ c finely diced red onion
1 tbsp finely diced jalapeño
2 tbsp fresh lime juice (1 lime)
1 garlic clove, minced
1 tbsp finely chopped fresh cilantro leaves
1 tsp avocado oil
½ tsp kosher salt
2 tbsp avocado oil
2 lbs ground chicken thighs
2 tsp chipotle chili powder
1 tsp kosher salt
½ tsp freshly ground black pepper
¼ c low-sodium chicken broth
1 tbsp tomato paste
6 @sietefoods Cassava Flour tortillas
2 avocados, mashed
½ c shredded purple cabbage
¼ c chopped fresh cilantro leaves

1. To make the tortillas, preheat the oven to 350°F and line a baking sheet with parchment paper. Place the tortillas in a single layer on the prepared baking sheet. Lightly spray the tops of the tortillas with nonstick cooking spray. Bake for 8 to 10 minutes, or until golden brown and crisp.
2. To make the salsa, toss together the pineapple, onion, jalapeño, lime juice, garlic, cilantro, avocado oil, and salt in a medium bowl. Refrigerate until ready to serve, up to 5 days. 
3. To make the chicken, heat the avocado oil over medium-high heat, in a large skillet. Add the ground chicken, chipotle chili powder, salt & pepper. Cook the chicken, breaking up the meat with the back of spoon, until it is brown, (~7 mins). Drain off any excess fat from the pan, if necessary. Reduce the heat to medium and add the chicken broth & tomato paste and stir to combine. Continue to cook for ~2 more minutes. Remove from heat & cover to keep warm until ready to serve.

node.text:
Strawberry Salad with Crispy Coppa and Seared Scallops for dinner tonight! An easy #ddsimplesummer dinner that I thoroughly enjoyed 

For the Salad:
8 thin slices of coppa (can sub prosciutto or salami)
3 cups baby arugula, packed
1 cup hulled and sliced strawberries
½ cup halved and thinly sliced red onion (or ¼ large onion)
½ jalapeno, seeds removed and very thinly sliced
¼ cup thinly sliced basil leaves 

For the Dressing:
2 tbsp evoo
2 cloves garlic, minced
1 tbsp balsamic vinegar
1 tbsp fresh lemon juice
½ tsp Dijon mustard

For the Scallops:
1 lb. sea scallops
1 tsp. Kosher Salt 
½ tsp black pepper
2 tbsp evoo

Method:

Preheat the oven to 400 degrees F. Place the coppa on a large baking sheet in a single layer so that none of the coppa is touching. When the oven is hot, bake until the coppa is just crisp, about 6 minutes. Set aside to let cool. 

Meanwhile, prepare your salad. In a large bowl, combine the arugula, strawberries, red onion, and basil. Set aside. 

In a small bowl, whisk together the olive oil, garlic, balsamic, lemon and Dijon until well combined. 

Pat the scallops very dry and season generously on both sides with kosher salt and pepper. Heat the EVOO in a large skillet over medium-high heat. When just starting to smoke, carefully place the scallops in the hot skillet and cook, undisturbed, until bottom has developed a golden crust, 2 to 3 minutes. Flip and cook until golden on the other side, 2 to 3 more minutes. Transfer to a plate and set aside. 

Drizzle the dressing over the salad and toss to coat. Divide the salad amongst 2 plates and top with the seared scallops. Roughly chop the crisp coppa and sprinkle over the top of the scallops and salad.

The Clayton’s Cocktail chapter has some fun, spirited beverages to pair with dinner or to kick off a fun evening. The cocktails can be perfectly paired with the appetizer chapter, which is filled with bites and dips for grazing before dinner or a fun happy hour with friends. And lastly—there is a Something Sweet chapter, with better-for-you desserts that I am so excited for you to try.

Similar to my first book, you’ll find a lot of the recipes are Paleo compliant—or at the very least Paleo-ish. Plus, there are plenty of recipes with simple ingredient swaps for a nutritious meal that everyone will love, making it perfect for people who are enjoying their "food freedom."

At the end of the day, food is a powerful way of expressing love and forming deeper connections with those around you and my hope is that as you cook your way through this book, you'll take the time to appreciate the way that food brings us all together.

Tonight’s #ddsimplesummer dinner: Greek Inspired turkey burgers with a simple cucumber-tomato salad and okra fries ☺️✨

1 lb. ground turkey (preferably dark meat)
2 cloves minced garlic
¼ cup pitted and roughly chopped kalamata olives
½ tsp ground cumin
1 tsp dried oregano
¼ tsp crushed red pepper flakes (optional)
½ tsp kosher salt
1 tbsp minced parsley leaves
1 tbsp minced dill fronds
1 tbsp. mayo
2 tbsp. tapioca flour
2 tbsp avocado oil

In a large bowl, combine the ground turkey, garlic, olives, cumin, oregano, red pepper flakes, salt, pepper, parsley, dill and mayo. Stir until well combined. Add in the tapioca starch and stir once more to combine. Using your hands, form the meat mixture into 4 equal patties. Because the turkey mixture will be a paste-like consistency, damp hands help in forming the patties more easily. Heat the oil in a non-stick skillet over medium-high heat. When hot, add the burgers and cook until golden brown and cooked through, about 3-4 mins per side. 

For the okra fries I simply cut off the cap and halve them. Drizzle with avocado oil and @humblesaltco toss to coat and bake at 375 for 25-30 mins. 

For the tomato salad: halve then slice a ripe tomato. Thinly slice 2 Persian cucumbers on the diagonal. Drizzle with good olive oil (I use @pineapplecollaborative) and @acidleague garden heat vinegar. Salt and pepper! 

That’s all! Yummy!
